</v:shape><![endif]--><!-- [if !vml]--><img src="/blogs/macroinvertebrates/Snail-Side.jpg" title="Snail-Side" alt="Snail" width="142" height="120"><!--[endif]--></span><span style="mso-tab-count: 1;" data-mce-style="mso-tab-count: 1;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: center; line-height: 200%;" data-mce-style="text-align: center; line-height: 200%;" align="center"><em style="mso-bidi-font-style: normal;" data-mce-style="mso-bidi-font-style: normal;">Examples of pollution-intolerant species</em></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 200%;" data-mce-style="line-height: 200%;"><br></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent: .5in; line-height: 200%;" data-mce-style="text-indent: .5in; line-height: 200%;">Other species of macros are tolerant to a wide range of water quality conditions. Their absence would signify poor water quality, while their abundance may not reveal much, since they would be present in all but the worst conditions. Examples in this category include crayfish, dragonfly nymphs, and scuds. <span style="mso-spacerun: yes;" data-mce-style="mso-spacerun: yes;">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 200%;" data-mce-style="line-height: 200%;"><br></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 200%; padding-left: 720px;" data-mce-style="line-height: 200%; padding-left: 720px;"><span style="mso-no-proof: yes;" data-mce-style="mso-no-proof: yes;"><!-- [if gte vml 1]><v:shape
