</v:shape><![endif]--><!-- [if !vml]--><img src="/blogs/macroinvertebrates/crayfish.jpg" alt="Crayfish" title="crayfish" width="226" height="177"></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 200%; padding-left: 520px;" data-mce-style="line-height: 200%; padding-left: 520px;"><br></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 200%; padding-left: 640px;" data-mce-style="line-height: 200%; padding-left: 640px;"><span style="mso-no-proof: yes;" data-mce-style="mso-no-proof: yes;"><!--[endif]--></span><em style="mso-bidi-font-style: normal;" data-mce-style="mso-bidi-font-style: normal;">Examples of species that tolerate a wide range of conditions.</em></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 200%;" data-mce-style="line-height: 200%;"><span style="mso-tab-count: 1;" data-mce-style="mso-tab-count: 1;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="text-indent: .5in; line-height: 200%;" data-mce-style="text-indent: .5in; line-height: 200%;">There are also certain species that generally tolerate pollution. When organisms in this group are dominant, that usually signals the water quality is fair to poor. Pouch snails, aquatic worms, roundworms, and leeches are a few of the pollution-tolerant types.</p><p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 200%; padding-left: 720px;" data-mce-style="line-height: 200%; padding-left: 720px;"><span style="mso-no-proof: yes;" data-mce-style="mso-no-proof: yes;"><!-- [if gte vml 1]><v:shape
